description: Travelling North - 6 orcas travelling tightly together - 1 had extremely large dorsal fin - couple small baby fins - others mid-size - viewed from San Juan County Park at the launching bay and from the top of the hill
Travelling North - Pod was east of channel closer to shore - no babies but many fairly large orcas - pod was spread out in pairs, singles
pod traveling south at san juan county park
Four Orca heading south at approximately Ayock Point

Watched a pod of at least 8 orcas pass by the Victoria golf and country club in an easterly direction about 200 ft from shore. Saw them again heading north east past oak bay marina but further out from shore.
A pod of 10 whales from young to adult.

Standing on the beach at the northern tip of Harstine island, looking north westerly (there's a bridge in the background) saw at least two maybe 3 orcas break through surface.  Pretty far from the shore but it was the coolest thing ever.
A pod of Orca head NB off Edmonds in the ferry traffic lanes.

MV Kennewick-Port Townsend Keystone run
0825:Master reports a pod of killer whales have been spotted in the northbound traffic lanes off of Keystone Harbor.  There are more than 12 whales.  They appear to be headed in the northbound direction while frolicking in breaching.  Orca Network notified.  No photographs available.
MV TILLIKUM-Fauntleroy Vashon Southworth run
0826hrs:
Chief Mate reports they have the spotted a small Humpback whale loitering between Vashon and Southworth.  This particular whale was spotted last week in the same vicinity.  Orca Network notified.  No photographs available at this time.
A pod of ORC (10-12) is off Grace Point, North of Fauntleroy, moving Northbound.
May include on juvenile.  Reported off Restoration Point. Picture taken off VASH earlier today by Bridget Soto.
Six-10 whales mid-channel off N. Vashon Head on the east side south bound.

Southworth terminal personnel report at least four orca whale just offshore in the vicinity of Lincoln Park/Coleman pool near the Fauntleroy terminal.  The whales appear to be traveling slowly in a southbound direction.

0820:
The Tacoma is westbound approaching Tyee Shoal at the entrance of Eagle Harbor.  
Master reports approximately 6 killer whales in the vicinity  of Tyee Shoal (entrance to Eagle Harbor).  They appear to be loitering, frolicking and feeding.  All whales appear to be adults.  Activity reported to the Whale Hotline/Orca Network.
0850:
The Chelan is westbound en route to Bremerton and holds Blakely Island abeam to the starboard.
Master reports approximately 8 adult killer whales in the vicinity of Blakely Island.  The pod appears to be feeding, frolicking and loitering.  
Also, the crew confirms  Tacoma's earlier observation of killer whale activity at Tyee Shoal.
0856:
The Kennewick is currently en route to Port Townsend and is crossing the traffic lanes.
Captain Miller reports there are approximately 6 to 8 killer whales which includes a very small killer whale, presumably a juvenile.  This pod is aggressively making way south in the southbound traffic lanes.  Orca Network notified

0730hrs Fauntleroy
Kitsap 's Master reports the vessel is en route to Fauntleroy and has reduced speed due to numerous killer whales in the area.  Information passed to the Orca Network.
1015hrs 
Kaleetan's Captain Corbin reports a plethora of killer whales just offshore between Duwamish Head and Alki Point.  They are displaying apparent feeding behavior.  Efforts will be made to take photographs and e-mail them to the operations center.  Orca Network notified.
1048hrs
Tacoma's Captain Merideth reports the pod of killer whales referred to earlier have moved in a northwesterly direction and are closing in the direction of Magnolia Bluff.  He estimates there are over a dozen whales.  Efforts will be made to take photographs and e-mail them to the operations center.  Orkin Network notified.
